@startuml
!theme plain
autonumber

box "Frontend System (Port SPA)" #LightCoral
    participant "Web Client (SPA/Browser)" as WebClient
    participant "Local Storage / Memory" as LocalStorage
end box

box "Backend System (Sistema AIT)" #LightBlue
    participant "HTTP Request" as HttpRequest
    participant "Route / Middleware" as Route
    participant "Auth Controller" as Controller
    participant "Auth Service" as AuthService
    box "Security" #LightYellow
        participant "Token Validator (JWKS / Introspect)" as TokenValidator
        participant "BCrypt Password Validator (legacy)" as PasswordVal
    end box
    box "Persistence" #LightGreen
        participant "User Repository" as Repo
    end box
end box

box "Identity Provider (IAM)" #LightGray
    participant "Authorization Endpoint (/authorize)" as IAMAuth
    participant "Token Endpoint (/token)" as IAMToken
    participant "JWKS / Introspection" as IAMJWKS
end box

' --- Login via Authorization Code + PKCE (SPA) ---
WebClient -> Controller : 1.0: User clicks "Login"
activate WebClient
activate Controller
Controller --> WebClient : 1.1: 302 Redirect to IAM /authorize (client_id, redirect_uri, code_challenge...)
deactivate Controller

WebClient -> IAMAuth : 1.2: Browser -> IAM (user authenticates)
activate IAMAuth
IAMAuth --> WebClient : 1.3: Redirect back to SPA with authorization code
deactivate IAMAuth

WebClient -> IAMToken : 1.4: POST /token (code + code_verifier) — exchange for access_token + id_token + refresh_token
activate IAMToken
IAMToken --> WebClient : 1.5: Tokens (access_token, id_token, refresh_token)
deactivate IAMToken

WebClient -> LocalStorage : 1.6: Store tokens (in-memory or secure storage; avoid localStorage if possible)
activate LocalStorage
LocalStorage --> WebClient : 1.7: Stored
deactivate LocalStorage

' --- Protected request with Bearer token ---
WebClient -> HttpRequest : 2.0: GET /api/protected (Authorization: Bearer <access_token>)
activate WebClient
activate HttpRequest
HttpRequest -> Route : 2.1: Middleware extracts Bearer token
activate Route
Route -> TokenValidator : 2.2: Validate token signature and claims (JWKS) OR call introspection
activate TokenValidator
TokenValidator -> IAMJWKS : 2.3: Retrieve JWKS / Introspect token
activate IAMJWKS
IAMJWKS --> TokenValidator : 2.4: Public keys / token active + claims
deactivate IAMJWKS
TokenValidator --> Route : 2.5: Token valid, attach user context
deactivate TokenValidator

Route -> Controller : 2.6: Forward request with user context
activate Controller
Controller -> AuthService : 2.7: Business logic (use user context)
activate AuthService
AuthService -> Repo : 2.8: Read domain data
activate Repo
Repo --> AuthService : 2.9: Domain data
deactivate Repo
AuthService --> Controller : 2.10: Result
deactivate AuthService
Controller --> HttpRequest : 2.11: HTTP 200 (resource)
deactivate Controller
HttpRequest --> WebClient : 2.12: Response (resource)
deactivate HttpRequest

deactivate WebClient

' --- Notes: legacy internal auth flow (kept for reference) ---
' If the system still issues its own JWTs, the flow would differ: authenticate credentials -> backend generates token -> client stores token.

@enduml
